      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im having some trouble with my deadlifts. my lower back is killing me every time i finish a set but i dont really feel it in my glutes or hamstrings like i should. what am i doing wrong with my form?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hoo-hoo! You have found your new best friend, the lower back! It is a very common and very annoying problem, and it is usually not a sign that you are doing something wrong, but rather that your body is trying to protect itself.\n\nFirst, let's talk about the mechanics of your lift. You are likely trying to lift your body weight with your legs, but your glutes and hamstrings are just the *muscles* doing the work, not the heavy machinery. Your lower back is the heavy machinery! If you are trying to lift with your back, you are essentially trying to lift a heavy rock with your hands while your back is the only thing holding it up. That is like trying to lift a car with your bare hands while your legs are the only thing supporting the weight.\n\nYou need to shift the load. Imagine your glutes and hamstrings are the sturdy wooden planks of a bridge, and your lower back is the weak rope. If you are pulling the rope with all your strength, the rope will snap. You need to let the planks do the lifting!\n\nHere is how to fix it:\n1.  **Bend at the hips, not the waist.** Think",
