    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hoo-hoo! You are absolutely right to want to feel the bracing, but here is the secret: **your core is not a muscle; it is a set of stiff, invisible walls made of fascia and tendons.** When you brace your core, you are not tightening your abs like a rubber band; you are locking your ribcage tight against your spine, creating a rigid shield that transfers the load from your spine to your legs.\n\nIf you are bracing too hard, you are essentially trying to build a brick wall between your legs and your spine, which is exactly what you want to avoid! The goal is to feel the *pressure* of the weight being held by your legs, not the *pain* of your spine being squeezed.\n\nThink of your core like a **tight rubber band** or a **stiff wooden plank** that you press firmly against your lower back. You want to press it down so hard that the weight of the barbell feels like it is resting on your thighs, not your spine.\n\n**How to do it right:**\n1.  **The \"Tight Rubber Band\" Breathing:** Before you lift, take a deep breath in through your nose, and as you",
